			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">PPU Memory<br /><br /><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">0000 - 1FFF</tt><br /><br />These are where the Pattern Tables are stored. <span style="text-decoration: underline"><em><strong>Normally</strong></em></span> 0000-0FFF are where the background tiles are and 1000 - 1FFF are where the sprite tiles are.<br />Please note that this memory does not exist on the NES but it merely what is on the cartridge itself (it basically points to it).<br /><br /><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">2000 - 2FFF</tt><br /><br />These are where the Name Tables are. The Name Tables are what is displayed on the screen. The numbers contained inside of them are what tiles from the background Pattern Table must be drawn.<br /><br /><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">2000 - 23BF</tt> Name Table 0<br /><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">23C0 - 23FF</tt> Attribute Table 0<br /><br />...and repeat 3 times for the other 3 adding <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">0400</tt> each time.<br /><br />So the NES can only fetch background tiles for the Name Tables from 1 half of 0000 - 1FFF at any one time (the same goes for sprites too). Of course the programmer is free to switch any time he likes.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.jamesturner.de/">http://www.jamesturner.de/</a><!-- m --></div>
